 range. The daily chart tells a clear story of progressive strength \u2014 from the congested 111.20\u2013112.00 band that dominated much of late June and early July, price has staged a measured but persistent advance, printing a sequence of higher lows and higher highs across the past fortnight. The move has not been explosive, but its structure is orderly and the bullish bias is well-supported by the price action itself.\n\nThe structure story begins with the breakout on 30 June, when a single daily candle cleared the prior range ceiling and closed at 112.50. That momentum stalled briefly, with price consolidating between 111.90 and 112.80 across the first week of July before a fresh leg higher emerged on 14 July. Since then, the pair has carved out a staircase pattern \u2014 each pullback finding support at progressively higher levels. The nearest prior reaction zone sits around 113.95, which has attracted buying on four separate occasions and now represents the first meaningful structural floor beneath current price. Beneath that, 113.20 and 112.85 serve as deeper reference points should the advance encounter more significant headwinds.\n\nOn the H1 timeframe, the intraday picture shows a brief dip through the European morning, with price touching 113.93 before buyers reasserted themselves firmly in the 11:00 UTC candle \u2014 a wide-range bar that drove directly into the 114.32 prior reaction zone and through it. The subsequent hourly candles have held above that level, with the most recent print at 114.43 suggesting the zone has flipped from potential resistance into near-term structural support. The intraday momentum is constructive, with no meaningful bearish follow-through visible on the shorter timeframe.\n\nToday's calendar is relatively light in terms of market-moving potential. Australian Flash Manufacturing and Services PMIs arrive at 19:00 UTC, followed by Japan's National Core CPI year-on-year and Flash Manufacturing PMI shortly after. All four releases carry a low-impact designation, meaning the desk would not ordinarily expect them to drive sustained directional moves. That said, any material surprise in Japanese CPI \u2014 particularly to the upside \u2014 could introduce short-term JPY strength and create a pullback scenario worth monitoring, given how extended the pair has become on a short-term basis.\n\nWhat would change the read? A decisive hourly close back beneath the 113.95 prior reaction zone would raise questions about the sustainability of today's push higher and shift the intraday picture to neutral. A daily close beneath 113.20 would represent a more meaningful structural deterioration and would challenge the broader bullish narrative. Until either of those scenarios materialises, the chart continues to favour the path of least resistance to the upside.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}